   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<b>Group</b><br>\n",
    "1. Ratish Moondra\n",
    "2. Ashwathy Gunadeep\n",
    "3. Narendra Sansoor\n",
    "\n",
    "<b>Problem Statement:</b><br>\n",
    "The problem addressed in this project is customer churn in the telecom industry. In this industry, customers have the ability to choose from multiple service providers, and switching from one provider to another is a common occurrence. Given the high cost of acquiring new customers, retaining existing ones has become increasingly important. Therefore, telecom companies need to identify which customers are at high risk of churning and take proactive steps to prevent churn. The project aims to analyze customer-level data of a leading telecom firm to build predictive models that can identify customers at high risk of churn and identify the main indicators of churn.\n",
    "\n",
    "<b>Machine Learning Objective:</b></br>\n",
    "The objective of the project is to predict churn in the last (i.e., the ninth) month using data from the first three months. The project will use a usage-based definition to define churn and focus on high-value customers, as approximately 80% of revenue comes from the top 20% customers in the Indian and Southeast Asian market. The predictive models should help identify high-churn-risk customers during the 'action' phase, where the customer starts to show different behavior than the 'good' months, so that corrective actions can be taken at this point to prevent churn.\n",
    "\n",
    "Approach We have taken is to train the data on 3 model (Logistic Regression, Random Forest, Decision Tree) and see which is the best performing model. We can enhance the same to perfom using the XGBoost and apply the concept for Bagging / Boosting."
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 235,

   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def unique_value_columns(input_df):\n",
    "    # Find out which columns have only 1 unique values\n",
    "    nunique_values = input_df.nunique() # Count the number of unique values in each column\n",
    "    unique_columns = nunique_values[nunique_values==1].index # Select columns with only 1 unique value\n",
    "    return unique_columns # Return the names of the selected columns\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def get_columns_with_missing_values_over_cutoff(input_df, cutoffpercentage, columns=None, verbose=False):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    This function calculates the percentage of missing values in each column of a Pandas DataFrame\n",
    "    and returns only the columns with missing values exceeding a specified cutoff percentage.\n",
    "\n",
    "    Parameters:\n",
    "    cutoffpercentage (numeric): The minimum percentage of missing values a column must have to be included.\n",
    "    columns (list, optional): A list of column names to include. If None, all columns are included.\n",
    "\n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "    A list containing only the columns with missing values exceeding the cutoff percentage.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "    assert isinstance(input_df, pd.DataFrame)\n",
    "    assert isinstance(cutoffpercentage, (int, float))\n",
    "    \n",
    "\n",
    "    # If columns are specified, calculate missing values only for those columns\n",
    "    if columns:\n",
    "        missing = round(df[columns].isnull().sum() / df.shape[0] * 100, 2)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Otherwise, calculate missing values for all columns\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        missing = round(df.isnull().sum() / df.shape[0] * 100, 2)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    if verbose:\n",
    "        print(missing.sort_values(ascending=False))\n",
    "        # print(missing.loc[missing > cutoffpercentage].index)\n",
    "        \n",
    "    # Return only columns with missing values exceeding the cutoff percentage\n",
    "    return list(missing.loc[missing > cutoffpercentage].index)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Define a custom Transformer class that drops columns from a Pandas DataFrame\n",
    "class DropColumns(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Initialize the class with the list of columns to drop\n",
    "    def __init__(self, columns_to_drop):\n",
    "        self.columns_to_drop = columns_to_drop\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Define the fit() method, which returns the transformer object\n",
    "    def fit(self, X, y=None):\n",
    "        return self\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Define the transform() method, which drops the specified columns from the input DataFrame\n",
    "    def transform(self, X):\n",
    "        if all(col in X.columns for col in self.columns_to_drop):\n",
    "            return X.drop(columns=self.columns_to_drop, inplace=True)\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            print(f\"Columns not found in the given data set. {self.columns_to_drop}.\\nHence cant be dropped.\")\n",
    "            return X\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def draw_churn_mou_graph(call_type, ax, regex, verbose=False):\n",
    "    col_list = high_value_users.filter(regex=regex).columns\n",
    "    if verbose:\n",
    "        print (col_list)\n",
    "    df1 = high_value_users.groupby([\"churn\"])[col_list].mean().T\n",
    "    ax.plot(df1)\n",
    "    ax.legend([\"Non-churn\", \"Churn\"])\n",
    "    ax.set_xticklabels([\"Jun\", \"Jul\", \"Aug\", \"Sep\"])\n",
    "    ax.set_title(f\"{call_type} MOU v/s Month\", loc=\"center\", fontsize=12, fontweight=0, color=\"red\")\n",
    "    ax.set_xlabel(\"Month\")\n",
    "    ax.set_ylabel(f\"{call_type} MOU\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Data Cleaning\n",
    "1. First cleanup/impute 50% or more empty columns \n",
    "2. Next cleanup/impute 5% or more empty columns \n",
    "3. Next cleanup/impute 2% or more empty columns \n",
    "4. Next cleanup/impute 0% or remaining empty columns"
   ]
  },

    "df.drop(columns=cols_to_drop, inplace=True, axis=1)"

   "source": [
    "#### Derive New Columns\n",
    "1. total volume data = 2g volume + 3g volume \n",
    "2. Average Recharg Amount = Total Recharge amount / Total Numer of Recharges \n",
    "3. Total Recharge Count for Data  = 2g Recharg Count + 3g Recharg Count\n",
    "4. Total Recharge Amount for Data  = [3] * [2]\n",
    "5. Total Month Recharge = Total Recharge Amount * Total Recharge Amount Data\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 263,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [

      "Columns: 206 entries, mobile_number to vbc_3g_9\n",
      "dtypes: datetime64[ns](4), float64(168), int64(34)\n",
      "memory usage: 156.6 MB\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "df.info()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 264,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "cols_to_drop = []\n",
    "for i in range(6,9):    # only process 6/7/8 month\n",
    "    cols_to_drop += [\"vol_2g_mb_\"+str(i), \"vol_3g_mb_\"+str(i), \n",
    "                    \"total_rech_amt_\"+str(i), \"total_rech_num_\"+str(i), \n",
    "                    'count_rech_2g_'+str(i), 'count_rech_3g_'+str(i), \n",
    "                    'total_rech_num_data_'+str(i), 'av_rech_amt_data_'+str(i), \n",
    "                    'total_rech_amt_'+str(i), 'total_rech_amt_data_'+str(i) ]\n",
    "\n",
    "    df[\"total_vol_data_mb_\"+str(i)] = (df[\"vol_2g_mb_\"+str(i)] + df[\"vol_3g_mb_\"+str(i)]).astype(int)\n",
    "    df[\"avg_rech_amt_\"+str(i)] = round(df[\"total_rech_amt_\"+str(i)] / (df[\"total_rech_num_\"+str(i)]+1),2)\n",
    "    df['total_rech_num_data_'+str(i)] = df['count_rech_2g_'+str(i)] + df['count_rech_3g_'+str(i)]\n",
    "    df['total_rech_amt_data_'+str(i)] = df['total_rech_num_data_'+str(i)] * df['av_rech_amt_data_'+str(i)]\n",
    "    df['total_month_rech_'+str(i)] = df['total_rech_amt_'+str(i)] * df['total_rech_amt_data_'+str(i)]\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "# Computing varios ratios for analysis\n",
    "for i in range(6,9): # as we have dropped the columns for month 9\n",
    "    high_value_users[\"og_to_ic_mou_\"+str(i)] = (high_value_users[\"total_og_mou_\"+str(i)]) / (high_value_users[\"total_ic_mou_\"+str(i)]+1)\n",
    "    high_value_users[\"loc_og_to_ic_mou_\"+str(i)] = (high_value_users[\"loc_og_mou_\"+str(i)]) / (high_value_users[\"loc_ic_mou_\"+str(i)]+1)\n",
    "    high_value_users[\"Total_loc_mou_\"+str(i)] = (high_value_users[\"loc_og_mou_\"+str(i)]) + (high_value_users[\"loc_ic_mou_\"+str(i)])\n",
    "    high_value_users[\"Total_roam_mou_\"+str(i)] = (high_value_users[\"roam_ic_mou_\"+str(i)]) + (high_value_users[\"roam_og_mou_\"+str(i)])"
   ]

   "source": [
    "from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "def plot_roc_curve2(y_true, y_score):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Plots the ROC curve given the true labels and predicted scores.\n",
    "\n",
    "    Parameters:\n",
    "    y_true (array-like): true binary labels (0 or 1)\n",
    "    y_score (array-like): predicted scores (usually probabilities)\n",
    "\n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "    None\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    # Compute the false positive rate, true positive rate, and threshold values using the `roc_curve` function\n",
    "    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_true, y_score)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Compute the area under the curve (AUC) using the `auc` function\n",
    "    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Plot the ROC curve\n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))\n",
    "    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange', lw=2, label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % roc_auc)\n",
    "    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')\n",
    "    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])\n",
    "    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])\n",
    "    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')\n",
    "    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')\n",
    "    plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve')\n",
    "    plt.legend(loc=\"lower right\")\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "    return fpr, tpr, thresholds"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 286,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, accuracy_score, precision_score, \\\n",
    "                            recall_score, f1_score,roc_auc_score, classification_report,balanced_accuracy_score\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def get_model_evaluation_metrics(y_true, y_pred, verbose=False):\n",
    "    # Calculate confusion matrix\n",
    "    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred).ravel()\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Calculate performance metrics\n",
    "    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)\n",
    "    precision = precision_score(y_true, y_pred, average='macro')\n",
    "    recall = recall_score(y_true, y_pred, average='macro')\n",
    "    f1 = f1_score(y_true, y_pred, average='macro')\n",
    "    roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_true, y_pred)\n",
    "    balanced_accuracy = balanced_accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Calculate additional metrics\n",
    "    specificity = tn / (tn + fp)\n",
    "    false_positive_rate = fp / (tn + fp)\n",
    "    positive_predictive_value = tp / (tp + fp)\n",
    "    negative_predictive_value = tn / (tn + fn)\n",
    "\n",
    "    if verbose:\n",
    "        print('Sensitivity/Recall : {}'.format(recall))\n",
    "        print('Specificity: {}'.format(specificity))\n",
    "        print('False Positive Rate: {}'.format(positive_predictive_value))\n",
    "        print('Positive predictive value: {}'.format(positive_predictive_value))\n",
    "        print('Negative Predictive value: {}'.format(negative_predictive_value))\n",
    "        print('-'*50)\n",
    "        print(\"Roc_auc_score : {}\".format(roc_auc))\n",
    "        print('Accuracy: {}'.format(accuracy))     \n",
    "        print('Precision: {}'.format(precision))     \n",
    "        print('Recall: {}'.format(recall))     \n",
    "        print('F1 score value: {}'.format(f1))     \n",
    "        print('Balanced Accuracy: {}'.format(balanced_accuracy))     \n",
    "\n",
    "     # Create a dictionary of results\n",
    "    metrics = {\n",
    "        'tn': tn,\n",
    "        'fp': fp,\n",
    "        'fn': fn,\n",
    "        'tp': tp,\n",
    "        'accuracy': round(accuracy*100, 2),\n",
    "        'precision': round(precision*100, 2),\n",
    "        'recall': round(recall*100, 2),\n",
    "        'f1': f1,\n",
    "        'roc_auc': round(roc_auc*100, 2),\n",
    "        'balanced_accuracy': round(balanced_accuracy*100, 2),\n",
    "        'specificity': round(specificity*100, 2),\n",
    "        'false_positive_rate': round(false_positive_rate*100, 2),\n",
    "        'positive_predictive_value': round(positive_predictive_value*100, 2),\n",
    "        'negative_predictive_value': round(negative_predictive_value*100, 2)\n",
    "    }\n",
    "\n",
    "    return metrics\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 287,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def predict_churn_on_given_probability(model, X, y, probability_threshold):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Predict churn based on given probability threshold using the trained model.\n",
    "\n",
    "    Args:\n",
    "    - model: Trained classification model\n",
    "    - X: Input features for prediction\n",
    "    - y: Target labels for evaluation\n",
    "    - probability_threshold: Probability threshold for classifying churn\n",
    "\n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "    - y_df: DataFrame with predicted probabilities, final predictions, and evaluation metrics\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Predict probabilities of churn\n",
    "    pred_prob = model.predict_proba(X)[:, 1]\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Create a DataFrame with actual churn labels and predicted probabilities\n",
    "    y_df = pd.DataFrame({'churn': y, 'churn_prob': pred_prob, 'probability_cutoff' : probability_threshold})\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Apply probability threshold to make final churn predictions\n",
    "    y_df[\"final_prediction\"] = y_df[\"churn_prob\"].map(lambda x: 1 if x > probability_threshold else 0)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Evaluate model performance using evaluation metrics\n",
    "    metrices = get_model_evaluation_metrics(y_df[\"churn\"], y_df[\"final_prediction\"])\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Return DataFrame with predicted probabilities, final predictions, and evaluation metrics\n",
    "    return y_df, metrices"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 288,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score\n",
    "\n",
    "def fit_and_evaluate_model(model, X_train, y_train, perform_cross_validation=False, cv_folds=5, verbose=False, train=True):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Fits a model to the training data, generates predictions for the training data, and optionally\n",
    "    performs cross-validation using the ROC AUC score as the evaluation metric.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Parameters:\n",
    "    -----------\n",
    "    model : an instance of a machine learning model with a `fit` and `predict_proba` method\n",
    "    X_train : a numpy array or pandas dataframe containing the training data features\n",
    "    y_train : a numpy array or pandas series containing the training data labels\n",
    "    perform_cross_validation : boolean, whether to perform cross-validation (default=False)\n",
    "    cv_folds : int, the number of cross-validation folds (default=5)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "    --------\n",
    "    A dictionary containing the following performance metrics:\n",
    "    - train_accuracy\n",
    "    - train_precision\n",
    "    - train_recall\n",
    "    - train_f1\n",
    "    - train_roc_auc\n",
    "    - cv_mean_roc_auc (only if perform_cross_validation=True)\n",
    "    - cv_std_roc_auc (only if perform_cross_validation=True)\n",
    "    - cv_min_roc_auc (only if perform_cross_validation=True)\n",
    "    - cv_max_roc_auc (only if perform_cross_validation=True)\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    if train:\n",
    "        model.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "    y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train)\n",
    "    y_train_pred_prob = model.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1]\n",
    "\n",
    "    metrics = get_model_evaluation_metrics(y_train, y_train_pred, verbose)\n",
    "\n",
    "    if perform_cross_validation:\n",
    "        cv_scores = cross_val_score(model, X_train, y_train, cv=cv_folds, scoring=\"roc_auc\")\n",
    "        metrics[\"cv_mean_roc_auc\"] = np.mean(cv_scores)\n",
    "        metrics[\"cv_std_roc_auc\"] = np.std(cv_scores)\n",
    "        metrics[\"cv_min_roc_auc\"] = np.min(cv_scores)\n",
    "        metrics[\"cv_max_roc_auc\"] = np.max(cv_scores)\n",
    "        print(f\"CV Score\\nmean : {metrics['cv_mean_roc_auc']}\\nStd : {metrics['cv_std_roc_auc']}\\nMin : {metrics['cv_min_roc_auc']}\\nMax : {metrics['cv_max_roc_auc']}\\n\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    return metrics\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 289,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "\n",
    "def add_metrics_to_dataframe(metrics_collect, metrics_dict):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Adds a row of metrics to a pandas dataframe.\n",
    "\n",
    "    Parameters:\n",
    "        metrics_dict (dict): A dictionary of metrics with the metric names as keys.\n",
    "        df (pandas.DataFrame): The dataframe to which the metrics row will be added.\n",
    "\n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        pandas.DataFrame: The updated dataframe with the metrics row added.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # create a pandas dataframe from the metrics dictionary\n",
    "    df_row = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(metrics_dict, orient='index').T\n",
    "\n",
    "    # create an empty dataframe with the same columns as the input dataframe\n",
    "    metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=metrics_collect.columns)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # concatenate the metrics row with the empty dataframe and return the result\n",
    "    return pd.concat([metrics_collect, df_row], ignore_index=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "    \n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 290,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def calculateOptimalCutoffs(input_df):\n",
    "    # Add extra columns with probability thresholds\n",
    "    addExtraColumns = [float(x)/10 for x in range(10)]\n",
    "    for i in addExtraColumns:\n",
    "        input_df[i] = input_df[\"churn_prob\"].map(lambda x: 1 if x>i else 0)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Create a dataframe to store cutoff probabilities and their corresponding accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity values\n",
    "    cutoffs_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=[\"probability\", \"accuracy\", \"sensitivity\", \"specificity\"])\n",
    "    prob_thresholds = np.arange(0,1.1,0.1)\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Compute accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity for each cutoff probability\n",
    "    for i in addExtraColumns:\n",
    "        tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(input_df[\"churn\"], input_df[i]).ravel()   \n",
    "        all_observations = tn+fp+fn+tp\n",
    "        acc = accuracy_score(input_df[\"churn\"], input_df[i])\n",
    "        sensitivity = recall_score(input_df[\"churn\"], input_df[i])\n",
    "        specificity = tn / float(tn+fp)\n",
    "        # Store the cutoff probability and its corresponding accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity values in the dataframe\n",
    "        cutoffs_df.loc[i] = [i , acc, sensitivity, specificity]\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Plot the accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity values for each cutoff probability\n",
    "    ax = cutoffs_df.plot.line(x=\"probability\", y=[\"accuracy\", \"sensitivity\", \"specificity\"], figsize=(20,5))\n",
    "    ax.set_xticks(np.arange(0,1.0,0.02))\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Return the dataframe with optimal cutoff probabilities and their corresponding accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity values\n",
    "    return cutoffs_df\n"
   ]
  },

    "def plot_train_test_accuracy(scores_df, parameter_name):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Plot the training and test accuracy for a given hyperparameter across cross-validation folds.\n",
    "\n",
    "    Parameters:\n",
    "    scores_df (pandas.DataFrame): A DataFrame containing cross-validation results.\n",
    "    parameter_name (str): The name of the hyperparameter to plot.\n",
    "\n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "    None\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    # Create a new figure and plot the training and test accuracy scores for each hyperparameter value\n",
    "    plt.figure()\n",
    "    plt.plot(scores_df[\"param_\" + parameter_name].tolist(), scores_df[\"mean_train_score\"].tolist(), label=\"Training Accuracy\")\n",
    "    plt.plot(scores_df[\"param_\" + parameter_name].tolist(), scores_df[\"mean_test_score\"].tolist(), label=\"Test Accuracy\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Add labels for the x-axis, y-axis, and legend\n",
    "    plt.xlabel(parameter_name)\n",
    "    plt.ylabel(\"Accuracy\")\n",
    "    plt.legend()\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Show the plot\n",
    "    plt.show()\n"
   ]

    "#### Random Forest Model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 312,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "cell_enabled = False\n",
    "# The Random forest model is very expensive to run on each iteration of GridSearchCV. \n",
    "# I have run this model for all possible hyper parameter and created a random_forest_model_final \n",
    "# This flag controls which cell to not execute when running in sequence \n",
    "\n",
    "from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier\n",
    "from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV\n",
    "if (cell_enabled):  # this is being done purely for the Random Forest model as it is very expensive\n",
    "    #I Cant run this GRID in one-GO on my machine 42 minutes and still going on ...\n",
    "    #I will need to break this down one by one\n",
    "    param_grid = {'max_depth' : range(10,30,5), \n",
    "                'n_estimators' : range(40,140,35),\n",
    "                'max_features' : [4,8,14,20,24],\n",
    "                'min_samples_leaf' : [100,400,50],\n",
    "                'min_samples_split' : [100,400,50]\n",
    "                }\n",
    "    random_forest_model = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=random_state)\n",
    "    grid_search = GridSearchCV(random_forest_model, param_grid, cv=5, scoring=\"f1\", return_train_score=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 313,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if (cell_enabled):\n",
    "    param_grid = {'max_depth' : range(10,30,5) }\n",
    "    random_forest_model_1 = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=random_state)\n",
    "    grid_search = GridSearchCV(random_forest_model_1, param_grid, cv=5, scoring=\"f1\", return_train_score=True)\n",
    "    grid_search.fit(X_train_pca, y_train_resampled)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 314,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if (cell_enabled):\n",
    "    scores = grid_search.cv_results_\n",
    "    plot_train_test_accuracy(scores, \"max_depth\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 315,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if (cell_enabled):\n",
    "    param_grid = {'n_estimators': range(40, 140, 35)}\n",
    "    random_forest_model_2 = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=random_state, max_depth=20)\n",
    "    grid_search = GridSearchCV(random_forest_model_2, param_grid, cv=5, scoring=\"f1\", return_train_score=True)\n",
    "    grid_search.fit(X_train_pca, y_train_resampled)\n",
    "    scores = grid_search.cv_results_\n",
    "    plot_train_test_accuracy(scores, \"n_estimators\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 316,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if (cell_enabled):\n",
    "    param_grid = {'max_features' : [4,8,14,20,24]}\n",

   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In the telecom churn case, recall is an important metric because it measures the ability of a model to correctly identify all the customers who are likely to churn. In other words, it measures the proportion of actual churners that are correctly identified by the model.\n",
    "\n",
    "For a telecom company, identifying customers who are likely to churn is crucial because it provides an opportunity to take proactive measures such as targeted marketing campaigns or personalized offers to retain those customers. If the model has low recall, it means that the company is likely to miss a significant proportion of customers who are likely to churn, which could lead to lost revenue and a decrease in customer satisfaction. Therefore, optimizing for recall in this case is important to ensure that the company can take proactive measures to retain customers who are likely to churn.\n",
    "\n",
    "Looking at the \"recall\" column, we can see that the Random Forest model performed the best on both the train and test datasets, with recall values of 85.34% and 77.92%, respectively. The Logistic Regression and Decision Tree models had lower recall values.\n",
    "\n",
    "Therefore, based on the recall metric, the Random Forest model would be the best choice among these three models."
   ]
  }
